Hey everyone 👋 
Time for a quick **ComputeHorde progress update** — two weeks after our mid-term goals drop https://discord.com/channels/799672011265015819/1201941624243109888/1370003979546918952

📦 **Image preload via dynamic config**
- To speed up job execution, miners can now preload Docker images before the job starts. It’s controlled via dynamic config - a simple solution, miners should use it smartly.

🛡️ **DDoS Shield** is now fully deployed!
- Validators have published their keys (automatically), and miners can now run the shield. We're running two test miners — one using the shield, the other not (long story involving hotkey sharing 😅).

📊**Allowance calculations merged** 
- We now calculate the **maximum allowed compute time (in seconds)** for each **validator–miner pair**, based on the miner’s manifest and the validator’s stake.

🕵️ **Cheated job reporting improvements**
- Duplicate cheated job reports are now blocked
- Reports must be signed by the consumer that actually scheduled the job

⏱️ **Timeouts got a full overhaul**
- We’ve reworked the timeout system across all ComputeHorde layers. Now, the consumer sets the job duration and that time is preserved downstream. Miners will get rewarded based on that time — so it's in their best interest to complete early.
- Flow chart here (tech warning;) ) https://github.com/backend-developers-ltd/ComputeHorde/blob/master/docs/job_flow.md#organic-job-flow

🧭 **Fallback mechanism to RunPod merged**
- Implemented via **SkyPilot**, which should make it easy to add other providers later (own GPU hardware, alternative clouds, etc.). Not battle-tested yet, but code is in.

📡 **Job result upload response is now visible to the consumer**
- If something goes wrong while uploading results to the S3 response bucket, the SDK now exposes the HTTP response, making it easier to troubleshoot.
- Bonus: Output HTTP volumes using **POST requests** have been fixed — they now work with S3-compatible storage, giving better control over uploaded resources than PUT-based volumes.

🐍 **Lowered Python/btcli dependencies**
- Some subnets we’re working with during hordization still use older versions, so we relaxed our dependency requirements to support them.

🔥**Updated burn rate for miners**
- With the token price spiking, we’ve reduced the mining incentives to avoid burning excess funds before we actually need active miners.

🧱**Collateral contract integration merged**
- Validators that set up their EVM identity will now have it **work automatically** with the contract.
- However, we’re **delaying onboarding** validators for now — there’s a change in EVM key association algorithms on subtensor testnet, and we’ll wait for that to hit mainnet before moving forward.

⚙️ On the **#yuma3** front:
- The PR is still on testnet — very close to mainnet merge.
- Meanwhile, we’re polishing a new version of the simulator that can use actual subnet data to test different toggle settings and compare outcomes (dividends, bonds, etc.).

That’s it for now — **small steps, steady progress.** Onward 👣

**Hey everyone** 👋

Time for another ComputeHorde progress update — continuing from the last one two weeks ago: https://discord.com/channels/799672011265015819/1201941624243109888/1374368844898111550

---

🧠 **Yuma3 is live on mainnet!**

Subnet owners can now turn yuma3 on, when they do validators are rewarded for **detecting new leaders quicker**.
**Once a subnet enables Yuma3**, the validators are rewarded for more careful, higher-quality validation, on some subnets that can be achieved by throwing in more compute.

We’re now focusing on **evangelizing Yuma3** to subnet owners.
To support this, we are wrapping up the **Yuma Simulator**, which uses real subnet data to test toggle configs and forecast rewards.

---

🌐 **Hordization: 4 subnets in progress**

Progress is steady but understandably slow — contenerizing and offloading validation logic is no easy task.
Still, real validation jobs are starting to flow.

---

🧪 **Stabilization & dogfooding**

We’re actively hardening the system — lots of real subnet traffic, and lots of production issues uncovered & fixed:

- Disk mount issues on executors
- Facilitator CD quirks
- Missing logs (job refusal, cleanup, miner picks)
- Organic vs synthetic job priority
- ComputeHorde SDK requiring too-high Bittensor versions
- Executor clipping too agressively on missed peak cycles
- Jobs missing stderr

🔁 We also replaced the original Bittensor SDK with a **lightweight, robust alternative**:

- Simpler, less thread-intensive subtensor connection → more reliable weight setting
- Cleaner, more Pythonic chain reads
- Auto block context (no need to pass block number etc manually to every call)

It’s already in use inside ComputeHorde. We’ll publish it once it’s a bit more feature-complete.

---

🧱 **Collateral contract: first sn12 validator live**

Rizzo deployed the contract 🎉, other validators are following / will follow when they are closer to running organic jobs on the Horde

---

📡 **Streaming job support merged**

Streaming is about saving on spin-up time and improving responsivenes. It’s a key step toward  long-running tasks — a key enabler for hordizing some of the subnets.

---

🔥 **Burn vs. Recycle: still evaluating**

Yep — still thinking this through 😅
99.5% of miner incentives go to the `5GbURN...` address. The idea is to **recycle or burn them gradually**, but the real effect will only be felt **years later (post-halving)**.

The real question:
*In 2 years, will subnet fees be enough to sustain miners?*

We want to make this decision responsibly — but right now, we lack a bit of bandwidth. It’s important, but not urgent.

We understand the pressure to show that we’ll follow through — and we will. The tokens just sit idle for now (not staked to any validator, not benefiting anyone), so they do no harm in the meantime.

---

🧭 **What’s next?**

We’ll continue **evangelizing Yuma3**, helping subnets unlock better validation through faster leader detection (and compute needs).

At the same time, we’ll keep **stabilizing ComputeHorde**, so that when demand arrives — it delivers **unparalleled quality of service**.
